4.8 Phase changes
If a substance remains in a single phase, any change in thermal energy causes a change in temperature following Equation 4.21. But when a change, between solid, liquid, and gas, occurs, energy is consumed or released in the phase change, and does not show up in temperature. In systems with phase changes, it is necessary to track one or more specific phases as a state variable. We can think of the equations that relate energy transfer and phase change as linking equations. There are only two important parameters, which are physical constants: the heat of fusion \(h_f\) and heat of vaporization \(k_v\), both typically \(\kJpkg\). These constants directly link the mass-based rate of phase change to energy flow.
\[
\dot{m_m} = \frac{\dot{Q}} {h_f}
\]{eq-hf-link}
\[
\dot{m_v} = \frac{\dot{Q}} {h_v}
\]{eq-hf-link}
